<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900418-0027</DOCNO><DOCID>900418-0027.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Safeway Stores Inc.:   First-Quarter Net Rose 71%;   Improved Margins Are Cited</HL><DATE>04/18/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   X.SAF</CO><IN>EARNINGS (ERN)FOOD RETAILERS AND WHOLESALERS, CONVENIENCE STORES (FDR)</IN><LP>   Safeway Stores Inc. said first-quarter net income surged71% as a result of improved gross margins and a decline ininterest expense.   The Oakland, Calif., supermarket chain posted profit of$15.5 million, or 17 cents a share, up from $8.8 million, or12 cents a share, a year earlier. Safeway had 88.2 millionshares outstanding in the 1990 quarter ended March 24,compared with 79.7 million a year earlier.</LP><TEXT>   Safeway said revenue for the quarter grew about 3% to$3.34 billion from $3.23 billion. The company said theincrease came despite the fact that the important Eastershopping period occurred this year after the close of thequarter.   Safeway attributed its improved margins to the addition ofprofitable speciality departments in numerous stores, anaggressive merchandising campaign and a streamlining of itscompanywide buying practices. Safeway also said its interestexpense fell 6% in the quarter to $83.8 million from $89.2million a year earlier.   Safeway has been closely held since 1986, when it wastaken private in a $4.3 billion leveraged buy-out by KohlbergKravis Roberts andamp; Co. The company recently announced plans togo public again by offering 10 million, or 10%, of its shareslater this month.</TEXT></DOC>